=99s $139,272,500 of bond value, plus the $6,794,562 of accrued (which I=E2=
=80=99m figuring is paid at 100 cents on the dollar), for a total of $146,0=
67,062 of value, divided by the 23,280,295 shares is $6.27.


  [2] Two points here. One: Obviously this AMC bondholder was not looking f=
or a long-term long position in the stock; of course it was selling. Two: A=
MC=E2=80=99s announcement says =E2=80=9CPursuant to Section 3(a)(9) of the =
Securities Act of 1933, as amended (the =E2=80=98Securities Act=E2=80=99), =
the Common Stock issued in the Exchange Transactions were issued in each ca=
se to existing security holders of the Company exclusively in exchange for =
such holders=E2=80=99 securities and no commission or other remuneration wa=
s paid or given for soliciting the exchange.=E2=80=9D That is legalese for =
=E2=80=9Cthe bondholders can sell this stock right away.=E2=80=9D


  [3] Also, a majority of the votes cast that are not owned by Musk and his=
 brother. See page 160 of the proxy.


  [4] I=E2=80=99m assuming that Tesla could get a quorum =E2=80=94 a majori=
ty of all outstanding stock =E2=80=94 to vote one way or another. It=E2=80=
=99s a little unclear; retail is estimated at 42% and known-to-Bloomberg in=
stitutions are 46%.


  [5] And, again, a majority of the non-Musk-owned shares outstanding. This=
 is also on page 160 of the proxy.


  [6] What do we think about that name? I kind of like it; it=E2=80=99s a l=
ittle crypto joke while also being a good example of tradfi acronyming.


