<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic mechanics of a stablecoin are:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You send $1 to a stablecoin issuer.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It sends you back one stablecoin, w=
hich represents $1 on the blockchain.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">The issuer uses your $1 to buy Treasury bills that pay like 5% interest=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You don=E2=80=99t get the intere=
st.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When interest rates were lower, this was a bas=
ically sensible proposition: Stablecoin holders could get a crypto token re=
presenting a dollar, which helped in their crypto trading, and they missed =
out on a little interest, but not much. When interest rates are 5%, being a=
 stablecoin <em>issuer </em><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/35389736.258338/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2Fyd=
